    content: {
      concept: `# Cell Membrane Structure

## Overview

The cell membrane is a **selective barrier** that separates the intracellular from extracellular environment. It follows the **fluid mosaic model** proposed by Singer and Nicolson (1972).

## Basic Structure

### Lipid Bilayer (60% of membrane mass)
- **Phospholipids** (75%): Phosphatidylcholine, phosphatidylserine, phosphatidylethanolamine
- **Cholesterol** (20%): Modulates membrane fluidity
- **Glycolipids** (5%): Cell recognition, blood group antigens

### Membrane Asymmetry
| Leaflet | Enriched in | Function |
|---------|-------------|----------|
| **Outer (Exoplasmic)** | Phosphatidylcholine, sphingomyelin | Cell recognition, glycocalyx |
| **Inner (Cytoplasmic)** | Phosphatidylserine, phosphatidylethanolamine | Enzyme attachment, signaling |

> 💎 **High Yield**: Phosphatidylserine exposure (flippase failure) = apoptosis signal

## Membrane Proteins (40% of membrane mass)

### Classification by Association
\`\`\`
INTEGRAL PROTEINS (Intrinsic)
├── Transmembrane (most)
│   ├── Single-pass (Growth factor receptors)
│   └── Multi-pass (Ion channels, GPCR)
└── Lipid-anchored (GPI-linked)

PERIPHERAL PROTEINS (Extrinsic)
├── Electrostatically bound
└── Easily removed by salt/pH
\`\`\`

### Functional Classification
| Type | Examples | Function |
|------|----------|----------|
| **Transport** | Na+-K+ ATPase, glucose transporters | Ion/molecule transport |
| **Enzymatic** | Adenylyl cyclase, phospholipase C | Signal transduction |
| **Receptor** | Insulin receptor, β-adrenergic | Hormone/neurotransmitter binding |
| **Structural** | Spectrin, ankyrin | Cell shape, membrane stability |
| **Recognition** | MHC molecules, integrins | Cell identification, adhesion |

## Fluid Mosaic Model Features

### Membrane Fluidity
**Factors increasing fluidity:**
- ↑ Temperature
- ↑ Unsaturated fatty acids
- ↓ Cholesterol content
- ↓ Chain length

**Factors decreasing fluidity:**
- ↓ Temperature
- ↑ Saturated fatty acids
- ↑ Cholesterol content
- ↑ Chain length

### Lateral Diffusion vs Transverse Movement
- **Lateral**: Rapid (10^-8 cm²/sec) - proteins and lipids move within leaflet
- **Flip-flop**: Very slow (days-weeks) - requires flippase/floppase enzymes

## Glycocalyx

### Composition
- **Glycoproteins**: N-linked (Asn) and O-linked (Ser/Thr)
- **Glycolipids**: Gangliosides, cerebrosides
- **Proteoglycans**: Heparan sulfate, chondroitin sulfate

### Functions
1. **Cell recognition** (ABO blood groups)
2. **Protection** from mechanical damage
3. **Negative charge** (sialic acid residues)
4. **Adhesion** between cells

## Membrane Rafts

### Characteristics
- **Cholesterol-rich** microdomains
- **Sphingolipid-enriched** regions
- **Less fluid** than surrounding membrane
- **Platform** for signaling molecules

### Functions
- **Signal transduction** (GPCR clustering)
- **Membrane trafficking** (endocytosis)
- **Pathogen entry** (some viruses/toxins)

## Clinical Correlations

### Membrane Disorders
| Condition | Defect | Clinical Features |
|-----------|--------|-------------------|
| **Hereditary spherocytosis** | Spectrin/ankyrin mutations | Hemolytic anemia, spherocytes |
| **Paroxysmal nocturnal hemoglobinuria** | GPI anchor deficiency | Complement-mediated hemolysis |
| **Familial hypercholesterolemia** | LDL receptor mutations | Premature atherosclerosis |

### Drug-Membrane Interactions
- **Anesthetics**: Disrupt lipid bilayer organization
- **Digitalis**: Binds Na+-K+ ATPase
- **Cholesterol-lowering drugs**: Alter membrane composition`,
      keyPoints: [
