    id: 'ion-channels-carriers',
    subjectId: 'physiology',
    subspecialtyId: 'physiology-general',
    name: 'Ion Channels & Carriers',
    slug: 'ion-channels-carriers',
    description: 'Voltage-gated, ligand-gated, mechanically-gated channels, GLUT transporters',
    content: {
      concept: `# Ion Channels & Carriers

## Overview

Ion channels and carriers are specialized membrane proteins that selectively transport ions and molecules. **Channels** allow rapid ion flow down gradients, while **carriers** undergo conformational changes during transport.

## Ion Channels

### Basic Properties
- **Selective** permeability to specific ions
- **Rapid** transport (10⁶-10⁸ ions/sec)
- **Gating** mechanisms control opening/closing
- **No saturation** kinetics (unlike carriers)

### Classification by Gating Mechanism

#### Voltage-Gated Channels
\`\`\`
VOLTAGE-GATED Na⁺ CHANNELS:

Structure: α-subunit (4 domains × 6 transmembrane)
States: Closed → Open → Inactivated

Kinetics:
├── Activation (opening): ~0.1-0.5 ms
├── Inactivation: ~1-2 ms  
└── Recovery from inactivation: ~2-10 ms
\`\`\`

**Na⁺ Channel Subtypes:**
| Subtype | Location | Function | Pharmacology |
|---------|----------|----------|--------------|
| **Nav1.1-1.3** | CNS | Action potentials | Phenytoin, lamotrigine |
| **Nav1.4** | Skeletal muscle | Muscle excitation | Muscle relaxants |
| **Nav1.5** | Cardiac muscle | Cardiac AP | Antiarrhythmics |
| **Nav1.7-1.9** | Sensory neurons | Pain signaling | Local anesthetics |

**K⁺ Channel Subtypes:**
| Channel | Gating | Location | Function |
|---------|--------|----------|----------|
| **Kv1-4** | Voltage | Neurons, muscle | Repolarization |
| **KCNQ** | Voltage | Neurons | M-current (stabilizing) |
| **Kir** | Inward rectifier | Widespread | Resting potential |
| **KATP** | ATP-sensitive | β-cells, muscle | Metabolic coupling |
| **KCa** | Ca²⁺-activated | Neurons | Afterhyperpolarization |

**Ca²⁺ Channel Subtypes:**
| Type | Subtype | Location | Function | Blocker |
|------|---------|----------|----------|---------|
| **L-type** | Cav1.2, 1.3 | Muscle, neurons | Contraction, LTP | Dihydropyridines |
| **N-type** | Cav2.2 | Presynaptic | Neurotransmitter release | ω-conotoxin |
| **P/Q-type** | Cav2.1 | Presynaptic | Neurotransmitter release | ω-agatoxin |
| **R-type** | Cav2.3 | Neurons | Repetitive firing | SNX-482 |
| **T-type** | Cav3.1-3.3 | Pacemaker cells | Pacemaker activity | Ni²⁺ |

#### Ligand-Gated Channels
\`\`\`
IONOTROPIC RECEPTORS:

Excitatory:
├── Nicotinic ACh (Na⁺, K⁺, Ca²⁺)
├── AMPA glutamate (Na⁺, K⁺)  
├── NMDA glutamate (Na⁺, K⁺, Ca²⁺)
└── Kainate glutamate (Na⁺, K⁺)

Inhibitory:
├── GABAA (Cl⁻)
├── Glycine (Cl⁻)
└── 5-HT3 (Na⁺, K⁺)
\`\`\`

**Nicotinic Receptor Subtypes:**
- **Muscle type** (α₁β₁γδ): Neuromuscular junction
- **Neuronal type** (α₄β₂, α₇): CNS, autonomic ganglia

**GABA_A Receptor:**
- **Structure**: Pentameric (α₂β₂γ₁)
- **Modulators**: Benzodiazepines (↑frequency), barbiturates (↑duration)
- **Antagonists**: Bicuculline, picrotoxin

#### Mechanically-Gated Channels
| Channel | Location | Stimulus | Function |
|---------|----------|----------|----------|
| **ENaC** | Kidney, lung | Mechanical stress | Na⁺ reabsorption |
| **Piezo1/2** | Mechanoreceptors | Mechanical force | Touch sensation |
| **TRPV4** | Various tissues | Osmotic swelling | Volume regulation |
| **K2P** | Sensory neurons | Mechanical stretch | Mechanosensation |

### Special Channel Types

#### TRP Channels (Transient Receptor Potential)
| Subfamily | Channel | Stimulus | Sensation |
|-----------|---------|----------|-----------|
| **TRPV** | TRPV1 | Heat (>43°C), capsaicin | Burning pain |
| | TRPV2 | Heat (>52°C) | Noxious heat |
| | TRPV4 | Warmth (~27-35°C) | Warm temperature |
| **TRPM** | TRPM8 | Cold (<25°C), menthol | Cold sensation |
| **TRPA** | TRPA1 | Cold, irritants | Noxious cold, pain |

#### Connexins (Gap Junctions)
- **Cx43**: Heart, brain (most abundant)
- **Cx26**: Inner ear (deafness mutations)
- **Cx32**: Peripheral nerve (Charcot-Marie-Tooth)

## Carrier Proteins

### Characteristics
- **Saturable** kinetics (Km, Vmax)
- **Slower** than channels (10²-10⁴ molecules/sec)
- **Conformational changes** during transport
- **Specific** binding sites

### Glucose Transporters (GLUTs) - Detailed

#### GLUT1 (Brain/RBC)
- **Km**: 1-2 mM (high affinity)
- **Function**: Basal glucose uptake
- **Regulation**: Constitutive expression
- **Pathology**: GLUT1 deficiency syndrome

#### GLUT4 (Muscle/Adipose)
- **Km**: 5 mM (moderate affinity)
- **Regulation**: Insulin-dependent translocation
- **Mechanism**: 
  \`\`\`
  Insulin → IR → IRS → PI3K → Akt → AS160 → GLUT4 vesicles to membrane
  \`\`\`
- **Exercise**: Also stimulates GLUT4 (AMPK pathway)

#### GLUT2 (Liver/Pancreas)
- **Km**: 15-25 mM (low affinity)
- **Function**: Glucose sensor
- **Bidirectional**: Glucose in/out based on concentration
- **Diabetes**: Glucose sensing in β-cells

#### GLUT5 (Small Intestine)
- **Substrate**: Fructose (not glucose)
- **Function**: Fructose absorption
- **Regulation**: Diet-dependent expression

### Amino Acid Transporters

#### System A (Alanine preferring)
- **Substrates**: Alanine, serine, proline
- **Characteristics**: Na⁺-dependent, pH-sensitive
- **Regulation**: Hormones, amino acid availability

#### System L (Large neutral)
- **Substrates**: Leucine, phenylalanine, tyrosine
- **Characteristics**: Na⁺-independent antiporter
- **Clinical**: LAT1 in blood-brain barrier

#### System ASC
- **Substrates**: Alanine, serine, cysteine
- **Location**: Kidney, intestine
- **Function**: Renal reabsorption

### Neurotransmitter Transporters
| Transporter | Substrate | Location | Drug Target |
|-------------|-----------|----------|-------------|
| **DAT** | Dopamine | Dopaminergic neurons | Cocaine, amphetamine |
| **SERT** | Serotonin | Serotonergic neurons | SSRIs |
| **NET** | Norepinephrine | Noradrenergic neurons | TCAs, SNRIs |
| **GAT** | GABA | GABAergic neurons | Tiagabine |

## Channel Modulation

### Pharmacological Modulation
| Drug Class | Target | Mechanism | Clinical Use |
|------------|--------|-----------|-------------|
| **Local anesthetics** | Na⁺ channels | Use-dependent block | Pain relief |
| **Antiepileptics** | Na⁺ channels | Stabilization | Seizure control |
| **Ca²⁺ channel blockers** | L-type Ca²⁺ | Direct block | Hypertension |
| **K⁺ channel openers** | KATP | Direct activation | Vasodilation |
| **Benzodiazepines** | GABAA | Positive modulation | Anxiety, sleep |

### Pathophysiology
| Disease | Channel Defect | Symptoms |
|---------|----------------|----------|
| **Long QT syndrome** | K⁺ or Na⁺ channels | Cardiac arrhythmias |
| **Hyperkalemic periodic paralysis** | Na⁺ channels | Muscle weakness |
| **Episodic ataxia** | K⁺ or Ca²⁺ channels | Ataxia, vertigo |
| **Familial hemiplegic migraine** | Ca²⁺ channels | Migraine with aura |
| **Malignant hyperthermia** | RyR Ca²⁺ channels | Hyperthermia |

## Clinical Applications

### Drug Development Targets
**Ion channels** represent ~15% of all drug targets:
- **Cardiovascular**: Ca²⁺ blockers, K⁺ openers
- **Neurological**: Na⁺ channel modulators
- **Psychiatric**: GABAA enhancers

### Diagnostic Applications
- **Patch clamp**: Direct channel measurement
- **Voltage clamp**: Current measurement
- **Ion-selective electrodes**: Ion concentration

### Therapeutic Applications
- **Gene therapy**: Channel replacement
- **Pharmacochaperones**: Folding correction
- **Antisense oligonucleotides**: Expression modulation`,
      keyPoints: [
